text: There is a case to be made for the precision of technology in some areas of production - you often see docos about car manufacturing plants that use robots to a large degree; there are still people employed, but definitely fewer than when everything was operated by people. And you are correct, this can lead to a loss of jobs in industries such as this. The question about how people are able to earn money in a highly technological world is a huge one.

text: I think everyone should be "concerned with" understanding how artificial intelligence might influence our future as humans, however I don't think that it makes sense to be worried about artificial intelligence, because the term represents a complex and ever-developing multiplicity of technologies with widely different applications, time-frames and possible consequences. This is a overwhelming amount of information, which the average person cannot make reasonable predictions about without understanding of a range of subjects including computing, human psychology, and economics.

text: I am "concerned with" trying to learn as much as I can about how artificial intelligence may shape our human future, but worrying about it as a nebulous monster I don't understand, doesn't make sense to me. I think doing my best to pay attention to what developments are being made is important. However, attempting to be at peace with the the unpredictability of the future and what I cannot control, and doing my best to take responsibility for my own choices in how I live and use technology is more important a concern to me.
